description:
Decouple `ir_typer::build_call_graph` from `specs` registration.
After this, the typer's call graph is computed purely from the IR's
terminator structure plus `Prim::MakeClosure` edges — exactly the
shape `ir_lower::annotate_back_edges` (`src/ir_lower.rs:615`)
already uses.

## Change

### `src/ir_typer.rs:50` — new signature

```rust
fn build_call_graph(m: &Module) -> HashMap<FnId, HashSet<FnId>> {
    let mut g: HashMap<FnId, HashSet<FnId>> = HashMap::new();
    for f in &m.fns {
        let edges = g.entry(f.id).or_default();
        for b in &f.blocks {
            for stmt in &b.stmts {
                if let Stmt::Let(_, Prim::MakeClosure(lam, _)) = stmt {
                    edges.insert(*lam);
                }
            }
            match &b.terminator {
                Term::Call { callee, continuation, .. } => {
                    edges.insert(*callee);
                    edges.insert(continuation.fn_id);
                }
                Term::TailCall { callee, .. } => { edges.insert(*callee); }
                Term::CallClosure { continuation, .. }
                | Term::Receive { continuation } => {
                    edges.insert(continuation.fn_id);
                }
                _ => {}
            }
        }
    }
    g
}
```

### Callers

Both `:472` (initial-SCC computation) and `:577`
(per-pass scc-of recompute) drop the `specs` argument.

## What's removed

- `specs: &HashMap<(FnId, Vec<Descr>), FnTypes>` parameter from
  `build_call_graph` and both call sites' threading of it.
- The `any_key = vec![Descr::any(); n]` lookup at `:60-63` and the
  silent bail-out for fns lacking an any-key spec.
- `ft.fn_constants.get(closure)` closure-target resolution at
  `:89, :95`. Closure call edges become continuation-only.

## What's NOT changed

- `MakeClosure` edges (`:68-70`) stay: each fn that allocates a
  closure for lambda L gets an edge to L. This is a structural
  over-approximation that covers most closure-target cases without
  needing fn_constants.
- Tarjan SCC implementation. Unchanged.
- `caller_scc.contains(&callee)` widening predicate in
  `walk_spec_for_discovery`. Unchanged — it just now operates on a
  correct graph.

## Tests

- All existing tests must remain green.
- Add a regression test in `src/ir_typer.rs::tests` (or a new
  module): construct a Module with two fns where fn B is reachable
  from fn A via TailCall, and fn A is reachable from fn B via
  TailCall (mutual recursion across fns). Assert that
  `type_module(m).scc_of(A) == type_module(m).scc_of(B)` (same
  SCC). Today this fails for any pair without any-key specs;
  after this fix it passes.

## Why this is a precondition for .2

Without this fix, `lower_multi_clause`'s per-clause body cont fn
(fn_clause_N) ends up in its own singleton SCC. The recursive call
from fn_clause_1 → count outer doesn't trigger widening (because
they're not in the same SCC), so the recursive spec key never
broadens to [int, int]. Codegen then can't find a covering spec.

After .1, count outer ↔ fn_clause_1 form a real SCC, widening fires
at iter >= WIDEN_AT (3), and the [int, int] spec lands on count
outer as expected.
